{
	"info": {
		"_postman_id": "annual-rental-cat1-item-form",
		"name": "Annual Rental Property — Category 1 (Item form-data)",
		"description": "Tests **PUT** `{{base_url}}/items/{{item_id}}` with **multipart/form-data** (not raw JSON).\n\n**Dynamic input IDs**  \nThe API expects `inputs` keyed by **numeric `inputs.id`** from your database (not by `name`). Import `Category1-Input-Ids.postman_environment.json`, fill every `id_*` value, then select this environment before sending.\n\nExample SQL (run after seeding):\n```sql\nSELECT i.id, i.name\nFROM inputs i\nINNER JOIN screens s ON s.id = i.screen_id\nWHERE s.category_id = 1\nORDER BY s.id, i.id;\n```\n\n**Auth**  \nSet `token` (Sanctum bearer) on the environment.\n\n**Fixture files (workspace-relative)**  \nFile fields point at `postman/fixtures/sample.png`. You can move or replace them; in Apidog/Postman, re-pick files from the workspace if paths break after moving the collection.\n\n**Notes**  \n- `property_condition` sample value uses `renovated` to match `validation_rules` (`in:new,used,renovated`). If your radio `value` in DB is `renewed`, align seeder or request.\n- `benefits`: send multiple rows with the same key `inputs[ID][]` (one value per selected benefit).\n- `nearby_landmarks`: repeatable rows use `inputs[ID][0][name]`, `inputs[ID][0][distance]`, etc.",
		"schema": "https://schema.getpostman.com/json/collection/v2.1.0/collection.json"
	},
	"variable": [
		{
			"key": "base_url",
			"value": "http://localhost:8000/api"
		},
		{
			"key": "item_id",
			"value": "1"
		}
	],
